## 5. Data Flow

### 5.1 Mood Tracking Flow

```
Step 1: User opens /mood page
Step 2: Component mounts → useEffect fires
Step 3: supabase.from("mood_entries").select("*")
            .eq("user_id", auth.uid())
            .order("entry_date", { ascending: false })
            .limit(10)
Step 4: PostgreSQL executes query with RLS filter (user_id = auth.uid())
Step 5: PostgREST returns JSON array → component sets moodHistory state
Step 6: Parallel query fetches last 90 days for calendar/chart
Step 7: User taps mood emoji (e.g., 😊 = 4)
Step 8: selectedMood state updates → note textarea appears
Step 9: User taps "Save"
Step 10: If todayEntry exists:
            supabase.from("mood_entries").update({ mood, note }).eq("id", todayEntry.id)
         Else:
            supabase.from("mood_entries").insert({ user_id, mood, note, entry_date: today })
Step 11: PostgreSQL validates RLS → inserts/updates row
Step 12: Success toast shown → fetchMoodHistory() re-fetches → UI updates
```

### 5.2 Challenge Creation Flow

```
Step 1: User clicks "Create Challenge" on /challenges
Step 2: CreateChallengeDialog opens → form rendered
Step 3: User fills title, description, category, difficulty, tags, optional cover image
Step 4: User clicks "Publish"
Step 5: If coverFile exists:
            supabase.storage.from("challenge-covers")
                .upload(`${user.id}/${timestamp}-${filename}`, file)
            → getPublicUrl() → cover_image_url
Step 6: supabase.from("challenges").insert({
            user_id, title, description, category, difficulty,
            tags, deadline, cover_image_url, season
         })
Step 7: PostgreSQL validates RLS (auth.uid() = user_id) → inserts row
Step 8: Dialog closes → onCreated() callback → fetchChallenges() re-runs
Step 9: New challenge appears in the grid with 0 likes/participants
```

### 5.3 AI Prompt Generation Flow

```
Step 1: User selects categories + difficulty on /prompt
Step 2: User clicks "Generate"
Step 3: supabase.functions.invoke("generate-prompt", {
            body: { categories, difficulty, mode: "structured" }
         })
Step 4: Edge function receives request with JWT in Authorization header
Step 5: JWT validated via supabase.auth.getClaims(token)
Step 6: Random theme/style/subject selected from curated pools
Step 7: System + user prompts constructed with anti-repetition rules
Step 8: POST to https://ai.gateway.lovable.dev/v1/chat/completions
            model: "google/gemini-3-flash-preview"
Step 9: AI returns JSON: { category, difficulty, warmup, study, challenge }
Step 10: Edge function parses response (with fallback on parse failure)
Step 11: JSON returned to client → StructuredPromptDisplay renders three tiers
Step 12: User can copy individual prompts or save to prompt_favorites
```

### 5.4 Login Streak Flow

```
Step 1: User logs in → AuthContext updates → Dashboard mounts
Step 2: useLoginStreak() hook fires useEffect
Step 3: supabase.rpc("update_login_streak", { p_user_id: user.id })
Step 4: PostgreSQL function executes (SECURITY DEFINER):
         a. Verifies p_user_id = auth.uid() (prevents spoofing)
         b. Looks up existing user_streaks row
         c. If NOT FOUND → inserts new row (streak: 1)
         d. If last_login = today → returns current values (idempotent)
         e. If last_login = yesterday → increments current_streak
         f. If gap > 1 day → resets current_streak to 1
         g. Updates longest_streak if current > longest
         h. Updates row and returns {current_streak, longest_streak, last_login_date}
Step 5: Hook updates state → LoginStreakCard renders fire/trophy icons
```

### 5.5 Habit Completion Flow

```
Step 1: User taps habit checkbox on /habits
Step 2: toggleHabit(habitId) fires
Step 3: If not completed today:
            supabase.from("habit_completions").insert({
                user_id, habit_id, completed_date: today
            })
         → Check if yesterday was completed (last_completed_date === yesterday)
         → If yes: new_streak = current_streak + 1
         → If no: new_streak = 1
         → supabase.from("habits").update({
                streak: new_streak,
                last_completed_date: today
           })
Step 4: If already completed (un-toggle):
            supabase.from("habit_completions").delete()
                .eq("habit_id", id).eq("completed_date", today)
         → countStreakBackwards(habitId, yesterday):
              Queries completions descending from yesterday,
              counts consecutive days
         → supabase.from("habits").update({
                streak: recalculated_streak,
                last_completed_date: yesterday_or_null
           })
Step 5: fetchHabits() re-runs → UI updates
```

